The article discusses the issues with the current immigration system in the United States, specifically the practice of Chain Migration. This system allows immigrants to bring in their extended families, leading to a de-skilling of the labor force, lower wages, and increased deficit. It also argues that Chain Migration undermines national security by not having a merit-based evaluation for entrants, instead relying solely on familial relations. The article suggests that this system allows individuals to easily obtain green cards and become voting citizens with access to welfare and government benefits.